metadata.name: Poema #170
metadata.description:
A poem is sometimes clear and colorful. 
It can be sharp. 
It can be oneiric. 
Sometimes it is enigmatic and deep.

The starting point of this project is an investigation of typography. The construction of a visual poem without words. Where letters and other signs evoke movement, rhythm, sound, echo and silence. The work plays with processes of construction/deconstruction of characters, with the visibility or subtlety of typographic elements.

*'Poema' is part of the 'Visual Poetry' group show curated by Atelier (http://atelierart.io).

----------------------------------
Each iteration has:
-> an alternative version in Portrait format, activated by the [p] key
-> a meta-poem, built from the features' metadata, accessible in the browser console, activated by the [F12] key

----------------------------------
Features:
-> Encruzilhada (Crossroad) = 2 possibilities
-> 3 types of Reverberations 
-> 6 types of Luminescences 
-> 5 Color schemes
-> 14 Palettes 

* The names of the palettes pay homage to poets and artists who deal with the visuality of writing in their work. 7 palettes honor women, 7 palettes honor men. Almost all from Latin America.

----------control keys------------ 
[F12] access to the meta-poem on browser console 
----------------------------------
[p] alternate format portrait/square 
[o] border on/off 
[e] save image with 2000 pixels height
[m] save image with 4000 pixels height
[a] save image with actual size
----------------------------------
Depending on the size option, the render time can be long.

----------------------------------
Created with p5.js
Tested in Chrome and Firefox on both Windows and Mac OS.

----------------------------------

https://marcelonada.redezero.org/
@marcelonada

*If you use more than one wallet, or the address on the reserve list is your vault, contact me via one of my social networks up to 12 hours before the drop.

metadata.name: Dialog Box #129
metadata.description:
Dialog Box is a playful generative art project that invites viewers to engage with the concept of choice in the digital age. Inspired by the early Mac OS, the artwork presents an interface of two buttons, each symbolizing a choice steeped in 80s and 90s pop culture, from the serious to the lighthearted.

https://medium.com/@duaneking/dialog-box-by-duane-king-scott-brewer-and-adam-moliski-abab7afd3519

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #533
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: Universal Rayhatcher #547
metadata.description:
# What is this?

This is 6942 characters of highly experimental code.

This is a version of my rayhatcher framework (see https://www.fxhash.xyz/article/rayhatching-evolution) that can do literally everything. Or, at least anything you can do within 512 characters of Javascript code. Which is slightly more than a mortal brain can comprehend.

This is my answer to the question: What is the least restrictive set of parameters for fx(params)?

# Should I be minting this?

Depends if you know and like building SDF formulas. Otherwise probably not. Like I said, this is highly experimental code. But it's definitely worth checking the collection and/or secondary for cool stuff that is already minted.

# How does it work?

The minter designs an SDF (Signed Distance Function) which is rendered using my rayhatcher algorithm. They then use the SDF formula in the SDF Code parameter. It's not very complicated, just efficient.

You can press "h" to load the documentation and read about how everything works. Or you can press "d" to read the dev docs. 

# Anything else?

Don't forget that the "Title Seed" param also becomes the "Title" feature of the mint, so make it count.

The params, including the SDF code actually get saved on-chain. Even better, all params and the entire code required to reproduce the image are included in the SVG when saved. See https://twitter.com/piterpasma/status/1649071912742420482 .

(c) 2023 by Piter Pasma // https://piterpasma.nl

metadata.name: Annum #8543
metadata.description:
This project is being released in celebration of the 1 year aniversary of Achromat, my first release on fxhash. In addition to being inspired by Achromat, aspects of other previous projects have been incorporated. My deepest gratitude to all who have collected my work over the past year.

In live mode, add &size=<YOUR_PIXEL_SIZE> to change the pixel size of the image for export (Right click to save). For example, &size=4000 will set the width of the image to be 4000 pixels.

50% of primary sales go to Savepakistan.

metadata.name: ðolmen #11
metadata.description:
ðolmen is a generative art project by Diego Pintos.
It draws rectangles with points instead a plain color or border. With some variations in the distribution of this points, we get a kind of noise depth effect.

12 carefully selected palettes. Based in Art Masterpieces and in Nature.
· Gioconda (Leonardo da Vinci)
· Guernika (Pablo Picasso)
· Nighthawks (Edward Hopper)
· Meninas (Diego Velazquez)
· Judith beheading Holofernes (Caravaggio)
· Al Siq (nature)
· guacamayo (nature)
· Salamanca (nature)
· mostaza (nature)
· Timanfaya (nature)
· piedra (nature)
· firefall (nature)

ðolmen builds 10 compositions:
· Square
· PersonChen's Style
· Equilibrium
· Hanging
· Pyramid
· Row
· Column
· 3 columns (randomly aligned)
· 3 rows (randomly aligned)
· Frame

Density
· Tiny: Less than 35 rects. Rare
· Small: Less than 100 rects. Common.
· Medium: Less than 250 rects. Common.
· High: Less than 350 rects. Common.
· Massive: Less than 500 rects. Rare.
· Ultra: More than 500 rects. Rarest.

Rarities
· Rectangle filling type: Filled (95%) or unfilled (5%)
· Monochrome: Just black and white. Always unfilled. (1%)
· Dark mode: Dark background (20%). Dark mode can be monochrome.
· Habitable (90%). See humans later.

Humans
ðolmen can host tiny humans. Contains a little code that draws humans looking down, in order to to provide size perspective.

Minting
Each ðolmen contains all rarities inside. As a ðolmen collector, you can display your final piece in all available formats, and rarity owners can display the regular filled composition. In addition, this can help if you want to print one or more formats.

Tricks and Keys
ðolmen is responsive, you can zoom out your browser window and refresh to get a larger output.
's' save the current canvas
'd' toggle dark mode
'f' toggle fill mode
'm' toggle monochrome

More info and visual description:
https://thelirios.com/dolmen/

Licensed under CC BY-NC-SA 4.0
